Malaria is a protozoan parasitic infection, prevalent in the Tropical & Subtropical areas of the world.
Four species of plasmodium parasites are responsible for malarial infections in humans viz.
Falciparum infections are associated with Cerebral malaria and drug resistance
whereas vivax infection is associated with high rate of infectivity and relapse.
Differentiation between P.falciparum and P.vivax is of utmost importance for better patient

This is only a Screening Test. Reactive Results should be confirmed by confirmatory test.
Recommended test is NS1 Antigen by ELISA in the first 5 days of fever.
After 7-10 days of fever, the recommended test is Dengue fever antibodies IgG&lgM by ELISA
Dengue viruses belong to the family Flaviviridae and have 4 subtypes ( 1-4).
lt is transmitted by the mosquito Aedesalbopictus, widely distributed in Tropical and Subtropical areas of the world.
Dengue is considered to be the most important arthropod borne viral disease due to the human morbidity it causes.
The disease may be subcinical, self limiting, febrile or may progress to a severe form of Dengue shock syndrome.
NS1 antigen is present in high concentrations in the sera of Dengue infected patients during early clinical phase of the disease.
It is detected from the 1st to 9th day after the onset of fever in cases of both Primary & Secondary Dengue.
